Let $\mathbf{a}$ denote $\overrightarrow{OA},$ etc.  Then
\[\mathbf{g}_a = \frac{\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{d}}{3} = \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{d} - \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{a}) = \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{d} - \mathbf{a}).\]Similarly, $\mathbf{g}_b = \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{b}),$ $\mathbf{g}_c = \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{c}),$ and $\mathbf{g}_d = \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{d}).$

[asy]
unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;
pair[] G;

A = (0,0);
B = (7,1);
C = (5,-5);
D = (1,-3);
G[1] = (B + C + D)/3;
G[2] = (A + C + D)/3;
G[3] = (A + B + D)/3;
G[4] = (A + B + C)/3;

draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(G[1]--G[2]--G[3]--G[4]--cycle,red);
draw(A--G[2],dashed);
draw(B--G[3],dashed);
draw(C--G[4],dashed);
draw(D--G[1],dashed);

label("$A$", A, W);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, SW);
dot("$G_A$", G[1], SE);
dot("$G_B$", G[2], W);
dot("$G_C$", G[3], NW);
dot("$G_D$", G[4], NE);
[/asy]

Hence,
\[\overrightarrow{G_A G_B} = \mathbf{g}_b - \mathbf{g}_a = \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{b}) - \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{d} - \mathbf{a}) = \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{2a} - \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{d}).\]Similarly,
\begin{align*}
\overrightarrow{G_B G_C} &= \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{2b} - \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a}), \\
\overrightarrow{G_C G_D} &= \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{2c} - \mathbf{d} - \mathbf{b}), \\
\overrightarrow{G_D G_A} &= \frac{1}{3} (\mathbf{2d} - \mathbf{a} - \mathbf{c}).
\end{align*}Therefore,
\begin{align*}
\overrightarrow{G_A G_B} \times \overrightarrow{G_B G_C} &= \frac{1}{9} (\mathbf{2a} - \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{d}) \times (\mathbf{2b} - \mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a}) \\
&= \frac{1}{9} (\mathbf{2a} \times \mathbf{2b} - \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{2b} - \mathbf{d} \times \mathbf{2b} - \mathbf{2a} \times \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{b} \times \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{d} \times \mathbf{c}) \\
&= \frac{1}{9} (\mathbf{2a} \times \mathbf{2b} - \mathbf{2a} \times \mathbf{2d} - \mathbf{2c} \times \mathbf{2b} + \mathbf{2c} \times \mathbf{2d}) \\
&= \frac{1}{9} \cdot 4 (\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} \times \mathbf{d}).
\end{align*}Also,
\[\|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} \times \mathbf{d}\| = \|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} - \mathbf{d} \times \mathbf{c}\| = 2 [ABCD].\]Therefore,
\[[G_A G_B G_C G_D] = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{9}{4} \cdot (\|\mathbf{a} \times \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} \times \mathbf{d}\|)^2 = \frac{81}{8} [ABCD].\]Hence, $\frac{[G_A G_B G_C G_D]}{[ABCD]} = \boxed{\frac{81}{8}}.$

Let $O$ be the intersection of $\overline{AC}$ and $\overline{BD}.$

Let $M$ and $N$ be the midpoints of $\overline{AB}$ and $\overline{CD},$ respectively.  Then $G_C$ is the centroid of triangle $ABD$, so $G_C M$ is one-third the length of the median from $G_C$ to $\overline{AB}.$  But the medians of triangle $ABD$ are concurrent at $O,$ so $G_C M = \frac{2}{3} O G_C.$

Similarly, $G_A N = \frac{2}{3} O G_A.$

[asy]
unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;
pair[] G;
pair M, N, O;

A = (0,0);
B = (7,1);
C = (5,-5);
D = (1,-3);
G[1] = (B + C + D)/3;
G[2] = (A + C + D)/3;
G[3] = (A + B + D)/3;
G[4] = (A + B + C)/3;
M = (A + B)/2;
N = (C + D)/2;
O = intersectionpoint(A--C,B--D);

draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(G[1]--G[2]--G[3]--G[4]--cycle,red);
draw(G[3]--M);
draw(G[1]--N);
draw(O--G[3],dashed);
draw(O--G[1],dashed);

label("$A$", A, W);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, SW);
dot("$G_A$", G[1], SE);
dot("$G_B$", G[2], W);
dot("$G_C$", G[3], NW);
dot("$G_D$", G[4], NE);
label("$M$", M, NE);
label("$N$", N, SE);
label("$O$", O, S);
[/asy]

Hence,
\begin{align*}
[G_A G_B G_C G_D] &= [G_A G_B M] + [G_A G_C N] + [G_C G_D N] + [G_B G_D M] \\
&= \frac{2}{3} [G_A O M] + \frac{2}{3} [G_C O N] + \frac{2}{3} [G_C O N] + \frac{2}{3} [G_B O M] \\
&= \frac{4}{3} [ABCD].
\end{align*}Therefore, $\frac{[G_A G_B G_C G_D]}{[ABCD]} = \boxed{\frac{4}{3}}.$

Let $M$ be the midpoint of $\overline{AB},$ and define $N,$ $P,$ and $Q$ similarly.

[asy]
unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;
pair[] G, M, N, P, Q;

A = (0,0);
B = (7,1);
C = (5,-5);
D = (1,-3);
G[1] = (B + C + D)/3;
G[2] = (A + C + D)/3;
G[3] = (A + B + D)/3;
G[4] = (A + B + C)/3;
M[1] = (A + B)/2;
M[2] = (A + C)/2;
M[3] = (B + D)/2;
M[4] = (C + D)/2;
N[1] = (B + C)/2;
N[2] = (A + C)/2;
N[3] = (A + D)/2;
N[4] = (B + D)/2;
P[1] = (B + D)/2;
P[2] = (A + D)/2;
P[3] = (A + C)/2;
P[4] = (B + C)/2;
Q[1] = (C + D)/2;
Q[2] = (A + D)/2;
Q[3] = (A + B)/2;
Q[4] = (B + C)/2;

draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(G[1]--G[2]--G[3]--G[4]--cycle,red);
draw(M[1]--N[1]--P[1]--Q[1]--cycle,blue);
draw(M[2]--N[2]--P[2]--Q[2]--cycle,blue);
draw(M[3]--N[3]--P[3]--Q[3]--cycle,blue);
draw(M[4]--N[4]--P[4]--Q[4]--cycle,blue);

label("$A$", A, W);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, SW);
dot("$G_A$", G[1], SE);
dot("$G_B$", G[2], W);
dot("$G_C$", G[3], NW);
dot("$G_D$", G[4], NE);
dot("$M_A$", M[1], NE);
dot("$M_B$", M[2], NW);
dot("$M_C$", M[3], SW);
dot("$M_D$", M[4], SE);
dot("$N_A$", N[1], W);
dot("$N_B$", N[2], NE);
dot("$N_C$", N[3], SE);
dot("$N_D$", N[4], SW);
dot("$P_A$", P[1], E);
dot("$P_B$", P[2], SE);
dot("$P_C$", P[3], NW);
dot("$P_D$", P[4], SW);
dot("$Q_A$", Q[1], S);
dot("$Q_B$", Q[2], S);
dot("$Q_C$", Q[3], N);
dot("$Q_D$", Q[4], N);
[/asy]

Then $\triangle ABG_D \sim \triangle CEG_D$ by SAS, so $G_D$ is the center of a spiral similarity carrying $\overline{AB}$ to $\overline{CD}.$  It follows that $G_D$ is the Miquel point of $ABCD.$  By symmetry, $G_A,$ $G_B,$ and $G_C$ are also Miquel points of $ABCD.$

Furthermore, $M_A,$ $N_A,$ $P_A,$ and $Q_A$ are the midpoints of the sides of $\triangle BCD,$ so the area of $G_A G_B G_C G_D$ is half the area of $M_A N_A P_A Q_A.$  Therefore,
\[\frac{[G_A G_B G_C G_D]}{[ABCD]} = \frac{[M_A N_A P_A Q_A]}{2[ABCD]}.\]Let $BC = a,$ $CD = b,$ $DA = c,$ and $AB = d.$  Then
\begin{align*}
[M_A N_A P_A Q_A] &= \frac{1}{16} (a + c)(b + d)(a + b)(c + d) \\
&= \frac{1}{16} [(a + c)(b + d) + (a + b)(c + d)][(a + c)(b + d) - (a + b)(c + d)] \\
&= \frac{1}{16} [(a + c)(b + d) + (a + b)(c + d)][(a - c)(b - d)] \\
&= \frac{1}{16} [(a + c)(b + d) - (a + b)(c + d)][(a - c)(b - d)] \\
&= \frac{1}{16} (ad - bc)^2.
\end{align*}Then
\[\frac{[G_A G_B G_C G_D]}{[ABCD]} = \frac{\frac{1}{16} (ad - bc)^2}{\frac{1}{2} (ac + bd)} = \frac{(ad - bc)^2}{8(ac + bd)}.\]

Let $\mathbf{a}$ denote $\overrightarrow{OA},$ etc.  Then
\[\mathbf{g}_A = \frac{\mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{d}}{3},\]so
\[\mathbf{g}_A - \mathbf{a} = \frac{\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{a}}{3} + \frac{\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{a}}{3} + \frac{\mathbf{d} - \mathbf{a}}{3}.\][asy]
unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair A, B, C, D;
pair[] G;

A = (0,0);
B = (7,1);
C = (5,-5);
D = (1,-3);
G[1] = (B + C + D)/3;
G[2] = (A + C + D)/3;
G[3] = (A + B + D)/3;
G[4] = (A + B + C)/3;

draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(G[1]--G[2]--G[3]--G[4]--cycle,red);
draw(A--G[1],Arrow(6));
draw(B--G[2],Arrow(6));
draw(C--G[3],Arrow(6));
draw(D--G[4],Arrow(6));

label("$\mathbf{a}$", A, N);
label("$\mathbf{b}$", B, NE);
label("$\mathbf{c}$", C, SE);
label("$\mathbf{d}$", D, SW);
label("$\mathbf{g}_A$", G[1], SE);
label("$\mathbf{g}_B$", G[2], W);
label("$\mathbf{g}_C$", G[3], NW);
label("$\mathbf{g}_D$", G[4], NE);
[/asy]

Similarly,
\begin{align*}
\mathbf{g}_B - \mathbf{b} &= \frac{\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{b}}{3} + \frac{\mathbf{d} - \mathbf{b}}{3} + \frac{\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{b}}{3}, \\
\mathbf{g}_C - \mathbf{c} &= \frac{\mathbf{d} - \mathbf{c}}{3} + \frac{\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{c}}{3} + \frac{\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{c}}{3}, \\
\mathbf{g}_D - \mathbf{d} &= \frac{\mathbf{a} - \mathbf{d}}{3} + \frac{\mathbf{b} - \mathbf{d}}{3} + \frac{\mathbf{c} - \mathbf{d}}{3}.
\end{align*}Adding all these equations, we get
\[\mathbf{g}_A + \mathbf{g}_B + \mathbf{g}_C + \mathbf{g}_D = \mathbf{a} + \mathbf{b} + \mathbf{c} + \mathbf{d}.\]Hence,
\[[G_A G_B G_C G_D] = \frac{1}{4} [ABCD].\]Therefore, $\frac{[G_A G_B G_C G_D]}{[ABCD]} = \boxed{\frac{1}{4}}.$

Let $O$ be the intersection of the diagonals of $ABCD,$ and let $H_A,$ $H_B,$ $H_C,$ $H_D$ denote the orthocenters of triangles $BCD,$ $ACD,$ $ABD,$ and $ABC,$ respectively.

[asy]
unitsize(0.6 cm);

pair A, B, C, D, O;
pair[] G, H;

A = (0,0);
B = (7,1);
C = (5,-5);
D = (1,-3);
O = extension(A,C,B,D);
G[1] = (B + C + D)/3;
G[2] = (A + C + D)/3;
G[3] = (A + B + D)/3;
G[4] = (A + B + C)/3;
H[1] = B + C - D;
H[2] = A + C - D;
H[3] = A + B - D;
H[4] = A + B - C;

draw(A--B--C--D--cycle);
draw(G[1]--G[2]--G[3]--G[4]--cycle,red);
draw(H[1]--H[2]--H[3]--H[4]--cycle,blue);
draw(O--G[1],dashed);

label("$A$", A, W);
label("$B$", B, NE);
label("$C$", C, SE);
label("$D$", D, SW);
label("$O$", O, NW);
dot("$G_A$", G[1], SE);
dot("$G_B$", G[2], W);
dot("$G_C$", G[3], NW);
dot("$G_D$", G[4], NE);
dot("$H_A$", H[1], S);
dot("$H_B$", H[2], NE);
dot("$H_C$", H[3], NW);
dot("$H_D$", H[4], N);
[/asy]

Then $G_A G_B$ is parallel to $H_C H_D,$ $G_B G_C$ is parallel to $H_D H_A,$ $G_C G_D$ is parallel to $H_A H_B,$ and $G_D G_A$ is parallel to $H_B H_C.$

Furthermore, each of these pairs of lines are midlines of trapezoids $H_A H_B H_C H_D,$ $H_B H_C H_D H_A,$ $H_C H_D H_A H_B,$ and $H_D H_A H_B H_C,$ respectively.

Therefore, $G_A G_B G_C G_D$ is a parallelogram, and its area is half the area of $H_A H_B H_C H_D.$  Therefore,
\[\frac{[G_A G_B G_C G_D]}{[ABCD]} = \frac{[H_A H_B H_C H_D]/2}{[ABCD]} = \boxed{\frac{1}{2}}.\]

